}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 The players can only observe the history of their neighbors\rquote  actions. For simplicity, I assume pay-off is hidden until Section {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMsec_varies \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{3.3}}}. Specifically, first denote <<:$s\\geq 0$:>> be a period. Let <<:$H^0_\{i\}=\\\{ \\emptyset \\\}$:>> and let <<:$H^s_\{i\}=H^0_\{i\}\\times \\prod^s_\{t=1\}A_\{\\theta_i\}$:>> be the set of histories of actions played by player <<:$i$:>> up to period <<:$s$:>>. Let <<:$H^0_\{G_i\}=\\\{\\emptyset\\\}$:>> and let <<:$H^s_\{G_i\}=H^0_\{G_i\}\\times \\prod^s_\{t=1\}\\prod_\{j\\in G_i\}A_\{\\theta_j\}$:>> be the set of histories player <<:$i$:>> can observe up to period <<:$s$:>>. For convenience, also denote <<:$H^0=\\\{\\emptyset\\\}$:>>, <<:$H^s=H^0\\times \\prod^s_\{t=1\}\\prod_\{j\\in N\}A_\{\\theta_j\}$:>>, and <<:$H=H^0\\times \\prod^\{\\infty\}_\{s=1\}\\prod_\{j\\in N\}A_\{\\theta_j\}$:>> with generic element <<:$h\\in H$:>>. Up to period <<:$s$:>>, <<:$i$:>>\rquote s information sets about histories of actions is then <<:$\\mathcal\{H\}^s_\{G_i\}=\\\{\\\{h^s_\{G_i\}\\\}\\times \\prod_\{j\\notin G_i\}H^s_\{j\}\\\}_\{h^s\\in H^s\}$:>>, where <<:$h^s_\{G_i\}\\in H^s_\{G_i\}$:>>.\par
<<:\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \fi360 $i$:>>\rquote s pure strategy is a function <<:$\\tau_\{\\theta_i\}:(\\prod_\{j\\in G_i\}\\Theta_j)\\times \\bigcup^\{\\infty\}_\{s=0\}H^s_\{G_i\}\\rightarrow A_\{\\theta_i\}$:>>. For convenience, also denote <<:$\\tau=\\\{\\tau_\{\\theta_i\}\\\}_i$:>>. \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \fi360 The prior <<:$\\pi$:>>, the network <<:$G$:>>, and <<:$\\tau$:>> induce a joint distribution, denoted as <<:$\\gamma^\{\\pi,\\tau\}_G$:>>, over <<:$\\Theta\\times H$:>>. Given a realization <<:$(\\theta,h)$:>> according to <<:$\\gamma^\{\\pi,\\tau\}_G$:>>, let <<:$h^\{\\tau\}_\\theta$:>> be the realized sequence of actions generated by <<:$\\tau$:>> given <<:$\\theta$:>>. Denote <<:$\\alpha^\{\\pi,\\tau\}_\{G_i\}(\\theta, h^\{s\}|\\theta_\{G_i\},h^\{s\}_\{G_i\})$:>> as the conditional distribution over <<:$\\Theta\\times H^s$:>> conditional on <<:$\\theta_\{G_i\}\\in \\Theta_\{G_i\}$:>> and <<:$h^\{s\}_\{G_i\}\\in H^s_\{G_i\}$:>> induced by <<:$\\tau$:>> for player <<:$i$:>> at period <<:$s$:>>. For convenience, also denote <<:$\\beta^\{\\pi,\\tau\}_\{G_i\}(\\theta|\\theta_\{G_i\},h^\{s\}_\{G_i\})=\\sum_\{h^\{s\}\\in H^s\}\\alpha^\{\\pi,\\tau\}_\{G_i\}(\\theta, h^\{s\}|\\theta_\{G_i\},h^\{s\}_\{G_i\})$:>>. Finally, let <<:$E^\{\\delta\}_G(u_\{\\theta_i\}(\\tau)|\\alpha^\{\\pi,\\tau\}_\{G_i\}(\\theta, h^\{s\}|\\theta_\{G_i\},h^\{s\}_\{G_i\}))$:>> be <<:$i$:>>\rquote s continuation expected pay-off conditional on <<:$\\theta_\{G_i\}$:>> and <<:$h^\{s\}_\{G_i\}$:>> induced by <<:$\\tau$:>>. \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \fi360 Let <<:$\\mathcal\{A\}^s_\{G_i\}=\\mathcal\{P\}_\{G_i\}\\times \\mathcal\{H\}^s_\{G_i\}$:>> be <<:$i$:>>\rquote s information sets at period <<:$s$:>>, and let <<:$\\mathcal\{A\}_\{G_i\}=\\prod^\{\\infty\}_\{s=0\}\\mathcal\{A\}^s_\{G_i\}$:>> be <<:$i$:>>\rquote s information sets. The equilibrium concept here is the (week) sequential equilibrium. A (weak) sequential equilibrium is a pair of <<:$\\\{\\tau^\{*\}, \\alpha^\{*\}\\\}$:>>, where <<:$\\alpha^\{*\}$:>> is a collection of distributions over players\rquote  information sets with the property that, for all <<:$i$:>>, for all <<:$s$:>>, <<:$\\alpha^\{*\}_\{G_i\}(\\theta, h^\{s\}|\\theta_\{G_i\},h^\{s\}_\{G_i\})=\\alpha^\{\\pi,\\tau^\{*\}\}_\{G_i\}(\\theta, h^\{s\}|\\theta_\{G_i\},h^\{s\}_\{G_i\})$:>> whenever <<:$A^s_\{G_i\}\\in \\mathcal\{A\}^\{s\}_\{G_i\}$:>> is reached with positive probability given <<:$\\tau^\{*\}$:>>. For all <<:$i$:>>, for all <<:$s$:>>, the <<:$\\tau^\{*\}_\{\\theta_i\}$:>> maximize <<:$i$:>>\rquote s continuation expected pay-off conditional on <<:$\\theta_\{G_i\}$:>> and <<:$h^\{s\}_\{G_i\}$:>> <<:\\[E^\{\\delta\}_G(u_\{\\theta_i\}(\\tau_\{\\theta_i\},\\tau^\{*\}_\{-\\theta_i\})|\\alpha^\{\\pi,\\tau_\{\\theta_i\},\\tau^\{*\}_\{-\\theta_i\}\}_\{G_i\}(\\theta, h^\{s\}|\\theta_\{G_i\},h^\{s\}_\{G_i\}))\\]:>> for all <<:$h^\{s\}_\{G_i\}$:>>. \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \fi360 We say a prior <<:$\\pi$:>> over a finite set has full support if {\par
\pard\plain\s17\ql\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 {\b Definition 2.1} {\i <<:$\\pi$:>> has full support if and only if <<:$\\pi(\\theta)>0$:>> for all <<:$\\theta\\in \\Theta$:>>. }\par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 Given a network <<:$G$:>>, I am looking for a sequential equilibrium which is APEX. \par
{\pard\plain\s17\ql\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 {\b Definition 2.2} {\i A strategy <<:$\\tau$:>> is APEX if and only if, for all <<:$\\theta$:>>, there is a finite time <<:$T^\{\\theta\}$:>> such that the actions in <<:$h^\{\\tau\}_\{\\theta\}$:>> after <<:$T^\{\\theta\}$:>> repeats the static ex-post Pareto efficient outcome. }\par
}{\pard\plain\s17\ql\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \sb120 \fi0 {\b Definition 2.3} {\i  A sequential equilibrium <<:$(\\tau^\{*\},\\alpha^\{*\})$:>> is APEX if and only <<:$\\tau^\{*\}$:>> is APEX. }\par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 In other words, in APEX strategies, all the Rebels play {\b revolt} forever after some finite periods if there are more than <<:$k$:>> Rebels; otherwise, Rebels play {\b stay} forever after some finite periods. The definition of APEX directly implies that Rebels must tell if there are more than <<:$k$:>> Rebels or not in the equilibrium path as the following observation shows. This proof is in Appendix.\par
{\pard\plain\s17\ql\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 {\b Lemma 2.1} {\i {\*\bkmkstart BMlemma_learn}{\*\bkmkend BMlemma_learn} Given <<:$G$:>>, <<:$\\pi$:>>, <<:$\\delta$:>>, <<:$k$:>>. If a sequential equilibrium <<:$\\tau^*$:>> is APEX, then given a <<:$\\theta$:>>, there is a finite time <<:$T^\{\\theta\}_i$:>> for a Rebel <<:$i$:>> such that <<:$\\sum_\{\\theta:\\#[Rebels](\\theta)\\geq k\}\\beta^\{\\pi,\\tau^*\}_\{G_i\}(\\theta|h^\{s\}_\{G_i\})$:>> either <<:$=1$:>> or <<:$=0$:>> whenever <<:$s\\geq T^\{\\theta\}_i$:>>. }\par
