}}}}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 In Example \~{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMex_cycle_number_6 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{3.3}}}, there are 6 Rebels, while there are 5 Rebels in Example \~{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMex_cycle_number_5 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{3.2}}}. Suppose now we have a \ldblquote talking strategies\rdblquote . Rebel 3 and Rebel 5 can talk about \ldblquote how many\rdblquote  Rebels in their neighborhood to Rebel 1 and Rebel 2. Rebel 1 and Rebel 2 then talk with each other about \ldblquote how many\rdblquote  Rebels they have known conditional on Rebel 3 and Rebel 5\rquote s taking. In some ways, Rebel 1 and Rebel 2 can initiate the coordination to play revolt conditional on \lquote how many\rdblquote  Rebels they have known. The question is that Rebel 1 and Rebel 2 still don\rquote t know how many Rebels out there after Rebel 3 and Rebel 5\rquote s talking since Rebel 3 and Rebel 5 will reveal the same number in both cases. Thus, \ldblquote talking about how many" nearby Rebels is not enough, Rebels have to \ldblquote talking about the locations\rdblquote  of nearby Rebels to get APEX. \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \fi360 Only having \ldblquote talking strategies\rdblquote  to reveal both number and locations is, however, not enough to get APEX. Although Lemma \~{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMlemma_learn \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{2.1}}} shows that there is a timing such that each Rebel have known the relevant information, but it did not characterize how Rebels commonly known that. This higher-order information about \ldblquote Have some Rebels known relevant information? \rdblquote  is an apparently giant object in the private monitoring setting. Here, Rebels use several \ldblquote coordination sequences\rdblquote  to communicate this information by sending such sequences if they have known that some Rebels have known the relevant information.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \fi360 I construct an APEX equilibrium with a weaker sequential consistent by assuming an off-path belief which has a grim-trigger property. More specifically, if a Rebel detect a deviation, he form the off-path belief as <<:$\\sum_\{\\theta \\in \\\{\\theta:\\theta_j=Inert,j\\notin G_i\\\}\}\\beta^\{\\pi,\\tau\}_\{G_i\}(\{\\theta\}|h^\{s^\{'\}\}_\{G_i\})=1$:>> for all <<:$s^\{'\}\\geq s$:>>. I.e., a Rebel will think all players outside his neighborhood are Inerts and stop update his belief. Thus, if a Rebel has less than <<:$k$:>> Rebel neighbors, he will play {\b stay} forever. \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \fi360 The equilibrium is constructed by three steps as the following three subsections shows. In the first step, I define the {\i information hierarchy in <<:$G$:>>} which gives a characterization to specify which Rebels have to report their information in equilibrium and gives the notations in constructing equilibrium. In second step, I show Rebels\rquote  strategies by showing the binary <<:$\\\{\\textbf\{revolt\},\\textbf\{stay\}\\\}$:>>-sequences used in equilibrium path and give the belief updating in the path. Finally, I discuss such grim-trigger-like off-path belief in the third step and give the idea of proof to show Theorem \~{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMthm_main_result \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{2}}}. \par
