}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 Lemma \~{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMlemma_at_most_two_nodes \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{3.1}}} is crucial because <<:$C^t$:>>-nodes can identify each other by the following procedure. First, a <<:$C^t$:>>-node ,<<:$j$:>>, assume that one of his <<:$R^\{t-1\}$:>> neighbor, <<:$i$:>>, is a <<:$R^t$:>>-node. Second, he check if <<:$i$:>> is in <<:$C^t$:>> by checking the definition of <<:$C^t$:>>. Third, if <<:$i$:>> is identified as a <<:$C^t$:>> node, <<:$i$:>> is the only other candidate. Finally, he assume that <<:$i$:>> will do the same procedure to identify him. Since himself is a <<:$C^t$:>>-node, <<:$i$:>> must be able to identify him if <<:$i$:>> is a <<:$C^t$:>>-node, and thus both <<:$C^t$:>>-nodes can identify each other.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \fi360 If there are more than one <<:$C^t$:>> nodes, I pick a node who has smaller prime index to be a pivotal player{\cs62\super\chftn}
