\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 In previous subsections, I have listed the belief updating in equilibrium path by showing the the belief updating after observing various messages. Lemma \~{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMlemma_in_the_path \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{3.3}}} show that the equilibrium path is APEX where the consistent in-path belief updating is listed in Table \~{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMTable_blf_up_reporting \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{3}}}, \~{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMTable_blf_up_cdt11 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{5}}}, and \~{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMTable_blf_up_cdt12 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{8}}}. {\par
\pard\plain\s17\ql\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 {\b Lemma 3.3} {\i  If the state has strong connectedness, then for all <<:$n$:>>-person repeated <<:$k$:>>-Threshold game with parameter <<:$1\\leq k\\leq n$:>> played in any FFCCU network without cycles, the equilibrium is APEX. }\par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 For the histories outside of equilibrium path, they could be detectable or undetectable. The argument to prove Theorem \~{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMthm_main_result \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{2}}} is as follows. First, I use off-path belief to prevent players from making detectable deviations, such as deviations from playing the specified forms of sequences listed in Table \~{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMTable_msg_reporting \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{2}}} and \~{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMTable_msg_coordination \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{4}}}. Then I argue that any undetectable deviation made by a Rebel before he knows the relevant information, <<:$\\#[Rebels](\\theta)\\geq k$:>> or <<:$\\#[Rebels](\\theta)< k$:>>, will create noises in his own learning process and then reduce his own expected continuation pay-off. To see why making undetectable deviation will create noises to impede the learning process before he knows the relevant information, consider the case when a Rebel wants to mimic pivotal plays\rquote  behaviors by sending <<:$\\langle 1 \\rangle$:>>. According to Table \~{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMTable_blf_up_cdt11 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{5}}} and Table \~{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMTable_blf_up_cdt12 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{8}}}, the continuation playing by his neighbors after observing <<:$\\langle 1 \\rangle$:>> is to play {\b stay} forever or to play {\b revolt} forever. Since all his neighbors repeats the same action, he can not learn additional information about <<:$\\theta$:>>. When <<:$\\delta$:>> is high enough, since he can learn the relevant information by Lemma \~{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMlemma_learn \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{2.1}}} if he stay in the path, he is better off by staying in the equilibrium path to achieve the maximum static pay-off as 1 when <<:$\\#[Rebels](\\theta)\\geq k$:>> and achieve the maximum static pay-off as 0 when <<:$\\#[Rebels](\\theta)< k$:>>. Claim \~{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMclaim_can_not_pretend_almost_success \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{7}}} shows this argument.\par
