\pard\plain\s5\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \sb180 \fi0 3.3.1  Variation: Pay-off as signals\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 The assumption on the observability of pay-off can be relaxed without change the result in Theorem \~{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMthm_main_result \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{2}}}. One may consider a situation such that the static pay-off depends not only on joint efforts but also depends on other random effects, says the weather.{\cs62\super\chftn}
{\*\footnote\pard \s65\ql\fi-113\li397\lin397\f0\fs24{\cs62\super\chftn} e.g.,({SHADMEHR and BERNHARDT}, 2011)}
. Specifically, consider there is a public signal <<:$y\\in \\\{y_1,y_2\\\}$:>> generated by Rebels\rquote  actions. Let Rebel <<:$i$:>>\rquote s pay-off function be <<:$u_\{Rebel\}(a_\{Rebel_i\},y)$:>>, and let <<:$u_\{Rebel\}(\\textbf\{stay\},y_1)=u_\{Rebel\}(\\textbf\{stay\},y_2)=u_0$:>>. The distribution of <<:$y_1$:>> and <<:$y_2$:>> is {<<:\\begin\{eqnarray*\}
\par p_\{1s\} &=& \\mathrm \{Pr\}(y=y_1|\\#\\textbf\{revolt\}\\geq k) \\\\
\par p_\{1f\} &=& \\mathrm \{Pr\}(y=y_1|\\#\\textbf\{revolt\}< k) \\\\
\par p_\{2s\} &=& \\mathrm \{Pr\}(y=y_2|\\#\\textbf\{revolt\}\\geq k) \\\\
\par p_\{2f\} &=& \\mathrm \{Pr\}(y=y_2|\\#\\textbf\{revolt\}< k) 
\par \\end\{eqnarray*\}:>>} with {<<:\\begin\{equation\}
\par p_\{1s\}u_\{Rebel\}(\\textbf\{revolt\}, y_1)+p_\{2s\}u_\{Rebel\}(\\textbf\{revolt\}, y_2)>u_0>p_\{1f\}u_\{Rebel\}(\\textbf\{revolt\}, y_1)+p_\{2f\}u_\{Rebel\}(\\textbf\{revolt\}, y_2)
\par \\end\{equation\}:>>} and {<<:\\begin\{equation\}
\par 1>p_\{1s\}>0,1>p_\{2s\}>0,p_\{1f\}=1-p_\{1s\},p_\{2f\}=1-p_\{2s\}
\par \\end\{equation\}:>>}\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \fi360 Equation (6) is a generalization for the previous setting. Equation (7) is a full support assumption on signal <<:$y$:>>. \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \fi360 We can construct exactly the same equilibrium strategies by ignoring the noisy signal <<:$y$:>> when Equation (7) holds. By directly checking the equilibrium path constructed in previous sections (see also Table \~{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMTable_msg_reporting \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{2}}} and \~{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMTable_msg_coordination \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{4}}}), {\i at most one} Rebel playing {\b revolt} in a period before some Rebels play <<:$\\langle 1 \\rangle$:>>, and thus the signal <<:$y$:>> is not relevant before some Rebels play <<:$\\langle 1 \\rangle$:>>. Moreover, playing <<:$\\langle 1 \\rangle$:>> comes from a Rebel\rquote s observation in reporting period where Rebels\rquote  strategies are independent from <<:$y$:>>, and thus playing <<:$\\langle 1 \\rangle$:>> is independent from <<:$y$:>>. We then just check if a Rebel want to deviate to play <<:$\\langle 1 \\rangle$:>> to get additional information coming from <<:$y$:>>. According to equilibrium strategies in the path, however, playing <<:$\\langle 1 \\rangle$:>> will incur either coordination to {\b stay} or coordination to {\b revolt} after current block as Table \~{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMTable_blf_up_cdt11 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{5}}} and Table \~{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMTable_blf_up_cdt12 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{8}}} shows. Since signal <<:$y$:>> is noisy, and since Rebels\rquote  actions will repeat, he can not learn the relevant information. As the same argument in Claim \~{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMclaim_can_not_pretend_almost_success \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{7}}}, he is better off by staying in the equilibrium path.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \fi360 If Equation (7) fails, and so that the signal <<:$y$:>> is not noisy, says <<:$p_\{1s\}=p_\{2f\}=1$:>>, the equilibrium constructed in the previous section is no longer an equilibrium. However, another APEX equilibrium can be constructed by letting all Rebels play {\b revolt} in the first period, and then keep playing {\b revolt} or {\b stay} contingent on the signals <<:$y=y_1$:>> or <<:$y=y_2$:>> when <<:$\\delta$:>> is sufficiently high.\par
\pard\plain\s5\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \sb120 \fi0 3.3.2  Variation: Rebels with different levels of efforts\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 Consider a model in which players have different levels of efforts to contribute to a collective action. Let the set of states of nature be <<:$\\hat\{\\Theta\}=\\Theta \\times \\Xi$:>>, where <<:$\\Xi=\\\{1,2,...,k\\\}^n$:>>. Let <<:$\\hat\{\\theta\}=(\\theta,e)$:>>, where <<:$\\theta\\in \\Theta$:>> and <<:$e\\in \\Xi$:>>. <<:$\\hat\{\\theta\}$:>> is interpreted as a state of nature in which a player <<:$i$:>> could be either a Rebel or Inert with <<:$e_i$:>> efforts, where <<:$e_i\\in \\\{1,2,...,k\\\}$:>>. When a Rebel <<:$i$:>> plays {\b revolt}, he contributes <<:$e_i$:>> efforts to a collective action, while the success of such collective action requires <<:$k$:>> amount of efforts. If the collective action succeed, such Rebel <<:$i$:>> will get <<:$b_i>0$:>> as his reward. The pay-off structure is modified as the following. {\par
